{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488707"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:53:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:53:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"512"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/512"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.17,0.11,0.56,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"512"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41605"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/512"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"512"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26523"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"8842"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35337"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41605"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being hit in the right eye with a tennis ball whilst sitting in a park 40 minutes previously. He describes severe pain around the right eye. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears well, though is holding his hand over his right eye. His pulse rate is 55/min, blood pressure 118/80mmHg and remainder of vitals within normal limits. The physical examination findings raise suspicions of an underlying injury and a coronal CT scan is arranged (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings on physical examination would be most in keeping with the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bloody discharge from the right nostril","Clear discharge from the right nostril","Hyphaema","Diplopia on vertical gaze","Numbness of the right forehead"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe coronal CT scan shows a\u003Cstrong\u003E right orbital blow-out fracture\u003C/strong\u003E. Blunt trauma most commonly causes an orbital floor fracture as this is where the bone is thinnest. This can result in entrapment of the inferior rectus muscle resulting in \u003Cstrong\u003Ediplopia on vertical gaze \u003C/strong\u003E(upwards and downwards gaze will be affected).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe infraorbital nerve can be injured in orbital floor fractures resulting in anaesthesia in the ipsilateral cheek and side of nose. The injury is usually bruising, rather than severance and as such, the nerve will recover its function in weeks or a few months. \u003Cstrong\u003ENumbness of the right forehead\u003C/strong\u003E would be seen with supraorbital nerve injuries as opposed to infraorbital nerve injury. Although \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyphaema\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood or clear discharge from the nostril\u003C/strong\u003E may be associated with orbital trauma, they are not specific to an orbital floor fracture as seen in the coronal CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Orbital floor fractures may cause vertical diplopia secondary to inferior rectus entrapment."],"references":["Approach to Orbital Fractures After Athletic Injuries. Flynn J. Facial Plast Surg Clin North Am. 2022; 30:31-45."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26523"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"512"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1555"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1555"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9e37b5b2-1a9c-4e59-a0ac-9666167091dc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9e37b5b2-1a9c-4e59-a0ac-9666167091dc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":421,"height":448}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26523"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-20T11:58:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T10:36:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"512"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41605"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}